Mills said, "We fought during my tenure on climate change, moved forward on climate action, while this administration in Washington disparages and says it's not real."

Mills did not mention her primary opponent, Graham Platner, by name, but did offer a comparison.

“I'm the only one in this primary who's actually won an election,” Mills said. "I am tested. My life is an open book. I don't have any tattoos. Trust me on that."

One house party attendee asked Mills, now 78, how she would respond to the charge that she is too old to seek another office. Mills reiterated her pledge, if elected, to serve one six-year term in the Senate.

“I know that I can get there on day one without worrying about running for election,” Mills said. “I'm running for one term to get stuff done.”

Jennifer Southard, who hosted the party with her husband, likes Mills' experience: two terms as Maine’s first woman governor, following her breaking the glass ceiling as state attorney general and a district attorney.

Southard said, "I'm on Team Mills because I want to beat Susan Collins, and I think Janet Mills has the best chance to do it, because she's a proven leader, and she's a fighter."

